05341nam a22006855i 9780231554374DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1328134592  a97802315543747 a10.7312/para202062doi  a(DE-B1597)627213  a(OCoLC)1291597161  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD9000.6b.P373 2022 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a338.1/9223/eng/202201041 aParasecoli, Fabio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGastronativism :bFood, Identity, Politics /cFabio Parasecoli. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArts and Traditions of the Table: Perspectives on Culinary History00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION: ENTER GASTRONATIVISM -- tPART ONE. GASTRONATIVISM -- tChapter One DEFENDING PRIVILEGE: EXCLUSIONARY GASTRONATIVISM -- tChapter Two TOWARD A BETTER FUTURE: NONEXCLUSIONARY GASTRONATIVISM -- tPART TWO. THE POWER OF FOOD -- tChapter Three FOOD AND IDENTITY -- tChapter Four FOOD AND POWER -- tPART THREE. BORDERS AND FLOWS -- tChapter Five FOOD, NATIONS, AND NATIONALISM -- tChapter Six FOOD AND DIPLOMACY -- tChapter Seven NATIONAL PRODUCTS IN THE GLOBAL MARKET -- tPART FOUR. BETWEEN HERE AND THERE -- tChapter Eight MIGRANT FOOD -- tChapter Nine CONTAGIONS -- tCONCLUSION: WHAT FUTURE? -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Italian political right is outraged by halal tortellini and a pork-free lasagna served at the Vatican. In India, Hindu fundamentalists organize attacks on Muslims who sell beef. European anti-immigrant politicians denounce couscous and kebabs. In an era of nationalist and exclusionary movements, food has become a potent symbol of identity. Why has eating become so politically charged—and can the emotions surrounding food be redirected in a healthier direction?Fabio Parasecoli identifies and defines the phenomenon of “gastronativism,” the ideological use of food to advance ideas about who belongs to a community and who does not. As globalization and neoliberalism have transformed food systems, people have responded by seeking to return to their roots. Many have embraced local ingredients and notions of cultural heritage, but this impulse can play into the hands of nationalist and xenophobic political projects. Such movements draw on the strong emotions connected with eating to stoke resentment and contempt for other people and cultures.Parasecoli emphasizes that gastronativism is a worldwide phenomenon, even as it often purports to oppose local aspects and consequences of globalization. He also explores how to channel pride in culinary traditions toward resisting transnational corporations, uplifting marginalized and oppressed groups, and assisting people left behind by globalization. Featuring a wide array of examples from all over the world, Gastronativism is a timely, incisive, and lively analysis of how and why food has become a powerful political tool.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFood in popular culture. 0aFood industry and tradexSocial aspects. 0aFoodxPolitical aspects. 0aIdentity politics. 0aLocavores. 0aNativism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eB